messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full path:
  /notifications/{notificationId}

- Accepts all HTTP methods: false

- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- The readNotification method is annotated with @RequestMapping(value="/notifications/{notificationId}", method = RequestMethod.PUT), so the path is /notifications/{notificationId} and that method explicitly accepts PUT.
- There is a separate method deleteNotification annotated with @RequestMapping(value="/notifications/{notificationId}", method = RequestMethod.DELETE), so DELETE is also handled for the same path.
- No handler in the code maps that path without a method restriction (i.e. no mapping that would accept all methods), and there are no explicit mappings for HEAD, POST, OPTIONS, TRACE, GET or PATCH on that path. Per the instruction to base conclusions on the code (not framework/runtime behavior), those methods are therefore not accepted.
